english:
  title: A Refutation of the Buddhist Doctrine of Karmic Rebirth
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The endless generation of all things flows from the transformations of heaven and earth in perpetual motion. The Supreme Ultimate contains movement and stillness, from which yin and yang arise. Yin and yang interact and combine to complete the five elemental forces. Thus the true nature of the Limitless and Supreme Ultimate, the refined essence of yin, yang, and the five elements, mysteriously converge and crystallize, and all things are born again and again. What has already come passes away and does not return, while what has not yet come arrives to continue the sequence. Not a single breath interrupts this flow.

    The Buddhists say: when a person dies, the spirit does not perish but takes form again. From this arose their doctrine of karmic rebirth. The Book of Changes teaches: "By examining the beginning, we know the end, and thus we understand the principles of death and life." It also states: "Refined essence becomes substance; wandering spirits become transformation." The ancient worthies interpreted this as follows: Though heaven and earth's transformations produce endlessly, what gathers must disperse, and what is born must die. If we trace things to their origin and understand how they gather into life, we must then understand how they inevitably disperse into death. If we comprehend that life arises naturally from the transformation of vital energy, with no spirit lodged in some vast void from the beginning, then we know that upon death, this energy disperses along with the body, leaving no lingering form in dark emptiness.

    They further explained: "Refined essence becomes substance; wandering spirits become transformation." When the vital energies of heaven and earth mingle, substance takes form. When spirit-energy returns to heaven and the body returns to earth, transformation occurs. Refined essence becoming substance means the refinement and energy combine to form matter—the refinement is the corporeal soul, the energy is the ethereal spirit. Wandering spirits becoming transformation means the ethereal and corporeal souls part and scatter, undergoing change. This is transformation, not mere variation. Once transformation occurs, the solid decays, the existent vanishes, and nothing remains. Heaven and earth are like a furnace—though they produce myriad things, all are consumed and depleted. How could what has scattered reassemble, or what has departed return?

    Consider our own bodies: in a single breath exhaled and inhaled, the vital energy cycles—we call this one breath. What is exhaled is not what is inhaled. Thus human breath, like all things, flows endlessly, with what departs passing away and what comes continuing. This principle is evident.

    Observe external phenomena: a plant grows from root to trunk to branch to leaf to flower to fruit—all sustained by one vital energy. In spring and summer, this energy flourishes and blossoms bloom luxuriantly. In autumn and winter, it withdraws and blossoms fade and fall. When spring and summer return the following year, they bloom again—yet these are not the fallen leaves returning to their source to be reborn. Consider a spring from which we draw water each day for cooking and washing. The water vanishes without trace, yet the spring flows endlessly without cessation. These are not the drawn waters finding their way back to gush forth anew. Consider grain: plant ten measures in spring, harvest one hundred in autumn, and the yield multiplies a thousandfold. Grain, too, generates endlessly.

    Now applying the Buddhist doctrine of rebirth: they claim all things with blood and vitality possess a fixed number, coming and going without increase or decrease. Then heaven and earth's creation would be inferior to a farmer's productivity! Moreover, creatures of blood and vitality—whether human, bird, beast, fish, or insect—have fixed numbers. When one flourishes, another must diminish; when one diminishes, another must flourish. They cannot all flourish or diminish simultaneously. Yet observing history, we see that in flourishing ages, humans, birds, beasts, fish, and insects all thrive together; in declining ages, all diminish together. This proves that humans and all creatures arise from heaven and earth's vital energy. When this energy abounds, all flourish at once; when it wanes, all decline at once. This is manifest.

    I am troubled by how deeply the Buddhist doctrine of rebirth deceives the world. In secret harmony with heaven and earth's transformations, and in open verification through the generation of all things, I have arrived at this understanding. I hope those of like mind will use this as a mirror.

    Someone asked: "You cite the ancients' interpretation of the Book of Changes—that the ethereal spirit becomes transformation, with spirits ascending to heaven and bodies descending to earth. Is this not the same as the Buddhists' claim that the spirit does not perish at death?"

    I reply: In antiquity, fire in all four seasons was taken from wood—because fire already exists within wood, becoming flame when wood grows hot. Similarly, the ethereal spirit already exists within the body, becoming conscious spirit when the body warms. Thus we say, 'rub wood and fire emerges.' The Book of Changes also states: 'Form being complete, spirit manifests and consciousness arises'—form is body, spirit is the ethereal soul. Fire depends on wood to exist, just as spirit depends on body to live. When fire extinguishes, smoke rises toward heaven and ashes fall toward earth—as when humans die, spirit ascends to heaven and body descends to earth. Fire's smoke is the human spirit-breath; fire's ashes are the human body. Once vital fire is extinguished, smoke and ashes cannot recombine to form fire again. Similarly, after death, spirit and body cannot recombine to form a living being. Is this principle not abundantly clear?
